[3
Date: 18 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ABCNews.com [edited
<http://abcnews.go.com/sections/us/DailyNews/US_ANTHRAX.html>

New Anthrax Cases
-----------------
"At CBS, an employee has tested positive for cutaneous anthrax," Tom Ridge,
director of the new White House Office of Homeland Security, said,
referring to the easily treatable "skin" form of the disease. "[She has
been placed on antibiotics and is expected . to make a full recovery." The
employee, an assistant to CBS News anchor Dan Rather, is the third person
believed to have contracted cutaneous anthrax at a television network in New
York. The other 2 - a 7-month-old infant who visited ABCNEWS headquarters
and an assistant to NBC News anchor Tom Brokaw - are also responding well to
antibiotic treatment. Unlike the NBC case, where the infected staffer is
known to have opened and handled an anthrax-laced letter, the sources of
infection in the ABC and CBS incidents are unknown.
State officials in New Jersey, meanwhile, said that 2 postal workers in
Trenton who may have handled the NBC letter as well as a second
anthrax-laced letter mailed to Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle have also
tested positive for cutaneous anthrax. That brought the total number of
confirmed anthrax infections nationwide to 7, including 2 employees at
the tabloid publishing company American Media Inc. in Boca Raton, Fla., who
inhaled anthrax spores. One died earlier this month and a second is
recovering.
. Government 'More Coordinated Than Ever'
Amid widespread criticism that the Bush administration has been sending out
mixed signals, Ridge - the man charged with heading up the government's
effort to prepare for and respond to terrorist threats - gathered with 7
other key officials to reassure the public about the nature of the anthrax
threat and the nation's readiness for any further terror attacks. Ridge was
joined by Attorney General John Ashcroft , FBI Director Robert Mueller,
Surgeon General David Satcher, as well as high-ranking officials from the
Defense Department and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
The director later told reporters that one of his tasks is to make sure that
"alleged inconsistencies" in the information provided to the public by
various government officials and agencies "are few and far between."
. Anthrax Count
Inhalation infections:
Florida tabloid photo editor (Deceased)
Florida tabloid mailroom worker (Recovering)
Cutaneous infections:
Aide to NBC News anchor Tom Brokaw (Recovering)
Child of ABCNEWS producer (Recovering)
Aide to CBS News anchor Dan Rather (Recovering)
Two postal workers in New Jersey (Recovering
Exposures:
Six at Florida tabloid
Thirty-one at Hart Senate Office Building
[Plus Pataki police desk
. Anthrax Incidents Believed Linked
Federal investigators are pursuing possible links between anthrax attacks in
New York, Florida and Washington, D.C. Officials have said preliminary
testing appears to indicate the anthrax found at NBC News headquarters in
New York and American Media Inc. may be from the same strain, suggesting the
2 incidents may be linked. "These preliminary tests do not show any
differences between those 2 strains," said Mitch Cohen, director of the
CDC, which is overseeing the testing.
Senior law enforcement officials have told ABCNEWS investigators believe the
anthrax-laced letters sent to NBC News anchor Tom Brokaw and Senate Majority
Leader Tom Daschle are in fact connected. Both envelopes were postmarked in
Trenton, N.J., had prepaid postage and had similar block handwriting.
According to sources who have seen them, the handwritten letters inside were
both dated "11 Sep 2001," the date of the terrorist attacks in New York and
Washington, and contained the message, "Death to America. Death to Israel.
Allah is great." While the Brokaw letter began, "This is next. Take
penacilin [sic now," the Daschle letter began, "This is next. Take your
medicine."
But despite the similarities in the letters, sources said the
anthrax-contaminated powders they contained are very different: The
substance sent to Capitol Hill was white and appeared to have been
professionally manufactured, while the powder mailed to NBC was brown and
crude in comparison. Mueller, however, said today that samples of anthrax
from all of the cases were still being analyzed "to determine whether or not
there is a sole or single source of each of those attacks."
. With the number of people confirmed to have been infected by or exposed
to the potentially deadly bacteria growing, federal authorities today
offered a $1 million reward for information leading to the arrest and
conviction of anyone sending anthrax through the mail.
Additionally, the FBI is continuing its crackdown on those responsible for
the more than 3300 phony bioterrorism hoaxes the bureau has responded to
over the past 18 days. Ashcroft said today that 4 individuals have been
charged in connection with false anthrax threats this week.
--
